Recall that the second order Taylor polynomial of a function $f(x)$ at a
point $x = a$ is given by $T_{2}(x)$ where,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle T_{2}(x) = f(a) + f'(a)(x - a) + \frac{1}{2}f''(a)(x-a)^{2}
\end{align*}

In our case, $a=1$ and $f(x) = \arctan(x)$.

sols_latex:
For our problem, we have that $a = 1$ and $f(x) = \arctan(x)$.
Evaluating the derivatives, we get

\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \frac{1}{1 + x^{2}}, \quad f''(x) = \frac{-2x}{(1 + x^{2})^{2}}
\end{align*}
Thus,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f(1) = \arctan(1) = \frac{\pi}{4}, \quad f'(1) = \frac{1}{2}, \quad f''(1) = -\frac{1}{2}
\end{align*}
and so the 2nd order Taylor polynomial is

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}T_{2}(x) = \frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{1}{2}(x - 1) - \frac{1}{4}(x -1)^{2}}.
\end{align*}

